  <mainDescription>Project closure confirms completion and acceptance of project deliverables to the satisfaction of the project sponsor, and
        communicates final project disposition and status to all participants and stakeholders. Closing activities also include
        identification and capture of lessons learned and best practices, and archival of project deliverables for subsequent
        reference, organizational learning and reuse.&lt;br /></mainDescription>
  <keyConsiderations>Project closure has a positive effect on future projects if done thoughtfully and correctly.&lt;br /></keyConsiderations>
  <impactOfNotHaving>Missed opportunity for process improvement. Possible repetition of past project failures. No understanding of delivered
        value.&lt;br /></impactOfNotHaving>
  <reasonsForNotNeeding>Acceptance is always required. A low risk project may not require additional closure documentation.&lt;br /></reasonsForNotNeeding>
  <briefOutline>The project closure typically consists of:&lt;br />
         &lt;br />
         
        &lt;ul>
            &lt;li>
                Completion &amp;amp; acceptance
            &lt;/li>
            &lt;li>
                Lessons learned
            &lt;/li>
            &lt;li>
                Release of resources
            &lt;/li>
            &lt;li>
                Final accounting &amp;amp; reporting
            &lt;/li>
            &lt;li>
                Team celebrations&lt;br />
            &lt;/li>
        &lt;/ul>
        &lt;br /></briefOutline>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription>
